3/*++
4/* NAME
5/* verify 8
6/* SUMMARY
7/* Postfix address verification server
8/* SYNOPSIS
9/* \fBverify\fR [generic Postfix daemon options]
10/* DESCRIPTION
11/* The \fBverify\fR(8) address verification server maintains a record
12/* of what recipient addresses are known to be deliverable or
13/* undeliverable.
14/*
15/* Addresses are verified by injecting probe messages into the
16/* Postfix queue. Probe messages are run through all the routing
17/* and rewriting machinery except for final delivery, and are
18/* discarded rather than being deferred or bounced.
19/*
20/* Address verification relies on the answer from the nearest
21/* MTA for the specified address, and will therefore not detect
22/* all undeliverable addresses.
23/*
24/* The \fBverify\fR(8) server is designed to run under control
25/* by the Postfix
26/* master server. It maintains an optional persistent database.
27/* To avoid being interrupted by "postfix stop" in the middle
28/* of a database update, the process runs in a separate process
29/* group.
30/*
31/* The \fBverify\fR(8) server implements the following requests:
32/* .IP "\fBupdate\fI address status text\fR"
33/* Update the status and text of the specified address.
34/* .IP "\fBquery\fI address\fR"
35/* Look up the \fIstatus\fR and \fItext\fR for the specified
36/* \fIaddress\fR.
37/* If the status is unknown, a probe is sent and an "in progress"
38/* status is returned.
39/* SECURITY
40/* .ad
41/* .fi
42/* The address verification server is not security-sensitive. It does
43/* not talk to the network, and it does not talk to local users.
44/* The verify server can run chrooted at fixed low privilege.
45/*
46/* The address verification server can be coerced to store
47/* unlimited amounts of garbage. Limiting the cache expiry
48/* time
49/* trades one problem (disk space exhaustion) for another
50/* one (poor response time to client requests).
51/*
52/* With Postfix version 2.5 and later, the \fBverify\fR(8)
53/* server no longer uses root privileges when opening the
54/* \fBaddress_verify_map\fR cache file. The file should now
55/* be stored under the Postfix-owned \fBdata_directory\fR. As
56/* a migration aid, an attempt to open a cache file under a
57/* non-Postfix directory is redirected to the Postfix-owned
58/* \fBdata_directory\fR, and a warning is logged.
59/* DIAGNOSTICS
60/* Problems and transactions are logged to \fBsyslogd\fR(8).
61/* BUGS
62/* Address verification probe messages add additional traffic
63/* to the mail queue.
64/* Recipient verification may cause an increased load on
65/* down-stream servers in the case of a dictionary attack or
66/* a flood of backscatter bounces.
67/* Sender address verification may cause your site to be
68/* blacklisted by some providers.
69/*
70/* If the persistent database ever gets corrupted then the world
71/* comes to an end and human intervention is needed. This violates
72/* a basic Postfix principle.
73/* CONFIGURATION PARAMETERS
74/* .ad
75/* .fi
76/* Changes to \fBmain.cf\fR are not picked up automatically,
77/* as \fBverify\fR(8)
78/* processes are long-lived. Use the command "\fBpostfix reload\fR" after
79/* a configuration change.
80/*
81/* The text below provides only a parameter summary. See
82/* \fBpostconf\fR(5) for more details including examples.
83/* PROBE MESSAGE CONTROLS
84/* .ad
85/* .fi
86/* .IP "\fBaddress_verify_sender ($double_bounce_sender)\fR"
87/* The sender address to use in address verification probes; prior
88/* to Postfix 2.5 the default was "postmaster".
89/* .PP
90/* Available with Postfix 2.9 and later:
91/* .IP "\fBaddress_verify_sender_ttl (0s)\fR"
92/* The time between changes in the time-dependent portion of address
93/* verification probe sender addresses.
94/* CACHE CONTROLS
95/* .ad
96/* .fi
97/* .IP "\fBaddress_verify_map (see 'postconf -d' output)\fR"
98/* Lookup table for persistent address verification status
99/* storage.
100/* .IP "\fBaddress_verify_positive_expire_time (31d)\fR"
101/* The time after which a successful probe expires from the address
102/* verification cache.
103/* .IP "\fBaddress_verify_positive_refresh_time (7d)\fR"
104/* The time after which a successful address verification probe needs
105/* to be refreshed.
106/* .IP "\fBaddress_verify_negative_cache (yes)\fR"
107/* Enable caching of failed address verification probe results.
108/* .IP "\fBaddress_verify_negative_expire_time (3d)\fR"
109/* The time after which a failed probe expires from the address
110/* verification cache.
111/* .IP "\fBaddress_verify_negative_refresh_time (3h)\fR"
112/* The time after which a failed address verification probe needs to
113/* be refreshed.
114/* .PP
115/* Available with Postfix 2.7 and later:
116/* .IP "\fBaddress_verify_cache_cleanup_interval (12h)\fR"
117/* The amount of time between \fBverify\fR(8) address verification
118/* database cleanup runs.
119/* PROBE MESSAGE ROUTING CONTROLS
120/* .ad
121/* .fi
122/* By default, probe messages are delivered via the same route
123/* as regular messages. The following parameters can be used to
124/* override specific message routing mechanisms.
125/* .IP "\fBaddress_verify_relayhost ($relayhost)\fR"
126/* Overrides the relayhost parameter setting for address verification
127/* probes.
128/* .IP "\fBaddress_verify_transport_maps ($transport_maps)\fR"
129/* Overrides the transport_maps parameter setting for address verification
130/* probes.
131/* .IP "\fBaddress_verify_local_transport ($local_transport)\fR"
132/* Overrides the local_transport parameter setting for address
133/* verification probes.
134/* .IP "\fBaddress_verify_virtual_transport ($virtual_transport)\fR"
135/* Overrides the virtual_transport parameter setting for address
136/* verification probes.
137/* .IP "\fBaddress_verify_relay_transport ($relay_transport)\fR"
138/* Overrides the relay_transport parameter setting for address
139/* verification probes.
140/* .IP "\fBaddress_verify_default_transport ($default_transport)\fR"
141/* Overrides the default_transport parameter setting for address
142/* verification probes.
143/* .PP
144/* Available in Postfix 2.3 and later:
145/* .IP "\fBaddress_verify_sender_dependent_relayhost_maps ($sender_dependent_relayhost_maps)\fR"
146/* Overrides the sender_dependent_relayhost_maps parameter setting for address
147/* verification probes.
148/* .PP
149/* Available in Postfix 2.7 and later:
150/* .IP "\fBaddress_verify_sender_dependent_default_transport_maps ($sender_dependent_default_transport_maps)\fR"
151/* Overrides the sender_dependent_default_transport_maps parameter
152/* setting for address verification probes.
153/* SMTPUTF8 CONTROLS
154/* .ad
155/* .fi
156/* Preliminary SMTPUTF8 support is introduced with Postfix 3.0.
157/* .IP "\fBsmtputf8_autodetect_classes (sendmail, verify)\fR"
158/* Detect that a message requires SMTPUTF8 support for the specified
159/* mail origin classes.
160/* MISCELLANEOUS CONTROLS
161/* .ad
162/* .fi
163/* .IP "\fBconfig_directory (see 'postconf -d' output)\fR"
164/* The default location of the Postfix main.cf and master.cf
165/* configuration files.
166/* .IP "\fBdaemon_timeout (18000s)\fR"
167/* How much time a Postfix daemon process may take to handle a
168/* request before it is terminated by a built-in watchdog timer.
169/* .IP "\fBipc_timeout (3600s)\fR"
170/* The time limit for sending or receiving information over an internal
171/* communication channel.
172/* .IP "\fBprocess_id (read-only)\fR"
173/* The process ID of a Postfix command or daemon process.
174/* .IP "\fBprocess_name (read-only)\fR"
175/* The process name of a Postfix command or daemon process.
176/* .IP "\fBqueue_directory (see 'postconf -d' output)\fR"
177/* The location of the Postfix top-level queue directory.
178/* .IP "\fBsyslog_facility (mail)\fR"
179/* The syslog facility of Postfix logging.
180/* .IP "\fBsyslog_name (see 'postconf -d' output)\fR"
181/* The mail system name that is prepended to the process name in syslog
182/* records, so that "smtpd" becomes, for example, "postfix/smtpd".
183/* SEE ALSO
184/* smtpd(8), Postfix SMTP server
185/* cleanup(8), enqueue Postfix message
186/* postconf(5), configuration parameters
187/* syslogd(5), system logging
188/* README FILES
189/* .ad
190/* .fi
191/* Use "\fBpostconf readme_directory\fR" or
192/* "\fBpostconf html_directory\fR" to locate this information.
193/* .na
194/* .nf
195/* ADDRESS_VERIFICATION_README, address verification howto
196/* LICENSE
197/* .ad
198/* .fi
199/* The Secure Mailer license must be distributed with this software.
200/* HISTORY
201/* .ad
202/* .fi
203/* This service was introduced with Postfix version 2.1.
204/* AUTHOR(S)
205/* Wietse Venema
206/* IBM T.J. Watson Research
207/* P.O. Box 704

269 /*
270 * Silly little macros.
271 */
272#define STR(x) vstring_str(x)
273#define STREQ(x,y) (strcmp(x,y) == 0)

275 /*
276 * The address verification database consists of (address, data) tuples. The
277 * format of the data field is "status:probed:updated:text". The meaning of
278 * each field is:
279 *
280 * status: one of the four recipient status codes (OK, DEFER, BOUNCE or TODO).
281 * In the case of TODO, we have no information about the address, and the
282 * address is being probed.
283 *
284 * probed: if non-zero, the time the currently outstanding address probe was
285 * sent. If zero, there is no outstanding address probe.
286 *
287 * updated: if non-zero, the time the address probe result was received. If
288 * zero, we have no information about the address, and the address is being
289 * probed.
290 *
291 * text: descriptive text from delivery agents etc.
292 */
293
294 /*
295 * Quick test to see status without parsing the whole entry.
296 */
297#define STATUS_FROM_RAW_ENTRY(e) atoi(e)
298
299/* verify_make_entry - construct table entry */
300
301static void verify_make_entry(VSTRING *buf, int status, long probed,
302 long updated, const char *text)
303{
304 vstring_sprintf(buf, "%d:%ld:%ld:%s", status, probed, updated, text);
305}
306
307/* verify_parse_entry - parse table entry */
308
309static int verify_parse_entry(char *buf, int *status, long *probed,
310 long *updated, char **text)
311{
312 char *probed_text;
313 char *updated_text;
314
315 if ((probed_text = split_at(buf, ':')) != 0
316 && (updated_text = split_at(probed_text, ':')) != 0
317 && (*text = split_at(updated_text, ':')) != 0
318 && alldig(buf)
319 && alldig(probed_text)
320 && alldig(updated_text)) {
321 *probed = atol(probed_text);
322 *updated = atol(updated_text);
323 *status = atoi(buf);
324
325 /*
326 * Coverity 200604: the code incorrectly tested (probed || updated),
327 * so that the sanity check never detected all-zero time stamps. Such
328 * records are never written. If we read a record with all-zero time
329 * stamps, then something is badly broken.
330 */
331 if ((*status == DEL_RCPT_STAT_OK
332 || *status == DEL_RCPT_STAT_DEFER
333 || *status == DEL_RCPT_STAT_BOUNCE
334 || *status == DEL_RCPT_STAT_TODO)
335 && (*probed || *updated))
336 return (0);
337 }
338 msg_warn("bad address verify table entry: %.100s", buf);
339 return (-1);
340}
341
342/* verify_stat2name - status to name */
343
344static const char *verify_stat2name(int addr_status)
345{
346 if (addr_status == DEL_RCPT_STAT_OK)
347 return ("deliverable");
348 if (addr_status == DEL_RCPT_STAT_DEFER)
349 return ("undeliverable");
350 if (addr_status == DEL_RCPT_STAT_BOUNCE)
351 return ("undeliverable");
352 return (0);
353}
354
355/* verify_update_service - update address service */
356
357static void verify_update_service(VSTREAM *client_stream)
358{
359 VSTRING *buf = vstring_alloc(10);
360 VSTRING *addr = vstring_alloc(10);
361 int addr_status;
362 VSTRING *text = vstring_alloc(10);
363 const char *status_name;
364 const char *raw_data;
365 long probed;
366 long updated;
367
368 if (attr_scan(client_stream, ATTR_FLAG_STRICT,
369 RECV_ATTR_STR(MAIL_ATTR_ADDR, addr),
370 RECV_ATTR_INT(MAIL_ATTR_ADDR_STATUS, &addr_status),
371 RECV_ATTR_STR(MAIL_ATTR_WHY, text),
372 ATTR_TYPE_END) == 3) {
373 /* FIX 200501 IPv6 patch did not neuter ":" in address literals. */
374 translit(STR(addr), ":", "_");
375 if ((status_name = verify_stat2name(addr_status)) == 0) {
376 msg_warn("bad recipient status %d for recipient %s",
377 addr_status, STR(addr));
378 attr_print(client_stream, ATTR_FLAG_NONE,
379 SEND_ATTR_INT(MAIL_ATTR_STATUS, VRFY_STAT_BAD),
380 ATTR_TYPE_END);
381 } else {
382
383 /*
384 * Robustness: don't allow a failed probe to clobber an OK
385 * address before it expires. The failed probe is ignored so that
386 * the address will be re-probed upon the next query. As long as
387 * some probes succeed the address will remain cached as OK.
388 */
389 if (addr_status == DEL_RCPT_STAT_OK
390 || (raw_data = dict_cache_lookup(verify_map, STR(addr))) == 0
391 || STATUS_FROM_RAW_ENTRY(raw_data) != DEL_RCPT_STAT_OK) {
392 probed = 0;
393 updated = (long) time((time_t *) 0);
394 verify_make_entry(buf, addr_status, probed, updated, STR(text));
395 if (msg_verbose)
396 msg_info("PUT %s status=%d probed=%ld updated=%ld text=%s",
397 STR(addr), addr_status, probed, updated, STR(text));
398 dict_cache_update(verify_map, STR(addr), STR(buf));
399 }
400 attr_print(client_stream, ATTR_FLAG_NONE,
401 SEND_ATTR_INT(MAIL_ATTR_STATUS, VRFY_STAT_OK),
402 ATTR_TYPE_END);
403 }
404 }
405 vstring_free(buf);
406 vstring_free(addr);
407 vstring_free(text);
408}

410/* verify_post_mail_fclose_action - callback */
411
412static void verify_post_mail_fclose_action(int unused_status,
413 void *unused_context)
414{
415 /* no code here, we just need to avoid blocking in post_mail_fclose() */
416}
417
418/* verify_post_mail_action - callback */
419
420static void verify_post_mail_action(VSTREAM *stream, void *context)
421{
422
423 /*
424 * Probe messages need no body content, because they are never delivered,
425 * deferred, or bounced.
426 */
427 if (stream != 0)
428 post_mail_fclose_async(stream, verify_post_mail_fclose_action, context);
429}
430
431/* verify_query_service - query address status */
432
433static void verify_query_service(VSTREAM *client_stream)
434{
435 VSTRING *addr = vstring_alloc(10);
436 VSTRING *get_buf = 0;
437 VSTRING *put_buf = 0;
438 const char *raw_data;
439 int addr_status;
440 long probed;
441 long updated;
442 char *text;
443
444 if (attr_scan(client_stream, ATTR_FLAG_STRICT,
445 RECV_ATTR_STR(MAIL_ATTR_ADDR, addr),
446 ATTR_TYPE_END) == 1) {
447 long now = (long) time((time_t *) 0);
448
449 /*
450 * Produce a default record when no usable record exists.
451 *
452 * If negative caching is disabled, purge an expired record from the
453 * database.
454 *
455 * XXX Assume that a probe is lost if no response is received in 1000
456 * seconds. If this number is too small the queue will slowly fill up
457 * with delayed probes.
458 *
459 * XXX Maintain a moving average for the probe turnaround time, and
460 * allow probe "retransmission" when a probe is outstanding for, say
461 * some minimal amount of time (1000 sec) plus several times the
462 * observed probe turnaround time. This causes probing to back off
463 * when the mail system becomes congested.
464 */
465#define POSITIVE_ENTRY_EXPIRED(addr_status, updated) \
466 (addr_status == DEL_RCPT_STAT_OK && updated + var_verify_pos_exp < now)
467#define NEGATIVE_ENTRY_EXPIRED(addr_status, updated) \
468 (addr_status != DEL_RCPT_STAT_OK && updated + var_verify_neg_exp < now)
469#define PROBE_TTL 1000
470
471 /* FIX 200501 IPv6 patch did not neuter ":" in address literals. */
472 translit(STR(addr), ":", "_");
473 if ((raw_data = dict_cache_lookup(verify_map, STR(addr))) == 0 /* not found */
474 || ((get_buf = vstring_alloc(10)),
475 vstring_strcpy(get_buf, raw_data), /* malformed */
476 verify_parse_entry(STR(get_buf), &addr_status, &probed,
477 &updated, &text) < 0)
478 || (now - probed > PROBE_TTL /* safe to probe */
479 && (POSITIVE_ENTRY_EXPIRED(addr_status, updated)
480 || NEGATIVE_ENTRY_EXPIRED(addr_status, updated)))) {
481 addr_status = DEL_RCPT_STAT_TODO;
482 probed = 0;
483 updated = 0;
484 text = "Address verification in progress";
485 if (raw_data != 0 && var_verify_neg_cache == 0)
486 dict_cache_delete(verify_map, STR(addr));
487 }
488 if (msg_verbose)
489 msg_info("GOT %s status=%d probed=%ld updated=%ld text=%s",
490 STR(addr), addr_status, probed, updated, text);
491
492 /*
493 * Respond to the client.
494 */
495 attr_print(client_stream, ATTR_FLAG_NONE,
496 SEND_ATTR_INT(MAIL_ATTR_STATUS, VRFY_STAT_OK),
497 SEND_ATTR_INT(MAIL_ATTR_ADDR_STATUS, addr_status),
498 SEND_ATTR_STR(MAIL_ATTR_WHY, text),
499 ATTR_TYPE_END);
500
501 /*
502 * Send a new probe when the information needs to be refreshed.
503 *
504 * XXX For an initial proof of concept implementation, use synchronous
505 * mail submission. This needs to be made async for high-volume
506 * sites, which makes it even more interesting to eliminate duplicate
507 * queries while a probe is being built.
508 *
509 * If negative caching is turned off, update the database only when
510 * refreshing an existing entry.
511 */
512#define POSITIVE_REFRESH_NEEDED(addr_status, updated) \
513 (addr_status == DEL_RCPT_STAT_OK && updated + var_verify_pos_try < now)
514#define NEGATIVE_REFRESH_NEEDED(addr_status, updated) \
515 (addr_status != DEL_RCPT_STAT_OK && updated + var_verify_neg_try < now)
516
517 if (now - probed > PROBE_TTL
518 && (POSITIVE_REFRESH_NEEDED(addr_status, updated)
519 || NEGATIVE_REFRESH_NEEDED(addr_status, updated))) {
520 if (msg_verbose)
521 msg_info("PROBE %s status=%d probed=%ld updated=%ld",
522 STR(addr), addr_status, now, updated);
523 post_mail_fopen_async(make_verify_sender_addr(), STR(addr),
524 MAIL_SRC_MASK_VERIFY,
525 DEL_REQ_FLAG_MTA_VRFY,
526 SMTPUTF8_FLAG_NONE,
527 (VSTRING *) 0,
528 verify_post_mail_action,
529 (void *) 0);
530 if (updated != 0 || var_verify_neg_cache != 0) {
531 put_buf = vstring_alloc(10);
532 verify_make_entry(put_buf, addr_status, now, updated, text);
533 if (msg_verbose)
534 msg_info("PUT %s status=%d probed=%ld updated=%ld text=%s",
535 STR(addr), addr_status, now, updated, text);
536 dict_cache_update(verify_map, STR(addr), STR(put_buf));
537 }
538 }
539 }
540 vstring_free(addr);
541 if (get_buf)
542 vstring_free(get_buf);
543 if (put_buf)
544 vstring_free(put_buf);
545}
546
547/* verify_cache_validator - cache cleanup validator */
548
549static int verify_cache_validator(const char *addr, const char *raw_data,
550 void *context)
551{
552 VSTRING *get_buf = (VSTRING *) context;
553 int addr_status;
554 long probed;
555 long updated;
556 char *text;
557 long now = (long) event_time();
558
559#define POS_OR_NEG_ENTRY_EXPIRED(stat, stamp) \
560 (POSITIVE_ENTRY_EXPIRED((stat), (stamp)) \
561 || NEGATIVE_ENTRY_EXPIRED((stat), (stamp)))
562
563 vstring_strcpy(get_buf, raw_data);
564 return (verify_parse_entry(STR(get_buf), &addr_status, /* syntax OK */
565 &probed, &updated, &text) == 0
566 && (now - probed < PROBE_TTL /* probe in progress */
567 || !POS_OR_NEG_ENTRY_EXPIRED(addr_status, updated)));
568}

570/* verify_service - perform service for client */
571
572static void verify_service(VSTREAM *client_stream, char *unused_service,
573 char **argv)
574{
575 VSTRING *request = vstring_alloc(10);
576
577 /*
578 * Sanity check. This service takes no command-line arguments.
579 */
580 if (argv[0])
581 msg_fatal("unexpected command-line argument: %s", argv[0]);
582
583 /*
584 * This routine runs whenever a client connects to the socket dedicated
585 * to the address verification service. All connection-management stuff
586 * is handled by the common code in multi_server.c.
587 */
588 if (attr_scan(client_stream,
589 ATTR_FLAG_MORE | ATTR_FLAG_STRICT,
590 RECV_ATTR_STR(MAIL_ATTR_REQ, request),
591 ATTR_TYPE_END) == 1) {
592 if (STREQ(STR(request), VRFY_REQ_UPDATE)) {
593 verify_update_service(client_stream);
594 } else if (STREQ(STR(request), VRFY_REQ_QUERY)) {
595 verify_query_service(client_stream);
596 } else {
597 msg_warn("unrecognized request: \"%s\", ignored", STR(request));
598 attr_print(client_stream, ATTR_FLAG_NONE,
599 SEND_ATTR_INT(MAIL_ATTR_STATUS, VRFY_STAT_BAD),
600 ATTR_TYPE_END);
601 }
602 }
603 vstream_fflush(client_stream);
604 vstring_free(request);
605}
606
607/* verify_dump - dump some statistics */
608
609static void verify_dump(char *unused_name, char **unused_argv)
610{
611
612 /*
613 * Dump preliminary cache cleanup statistics when the process commits
614 * suicide while a cache cleanup run is in progress. We can't currently
615 * distinguish between "postfix reload" (we should restart) or "maximal
616 * idle time reached" (we could finish the cache cleanup first).
617 */
618 dict_cache_close(verify_map);
619 verify_map = 0;
620}
621
622/* post_jail_init - post-jail initialization */
623
624static void post_jail_init(char *unused_name, char **unused_argv)
625{
626
627 /*
628 * If the database is in volatile memory only, prevent automatic process
629 * suicide after a limited number of client requests or after a limited
630 * amount of idle time.
631 */
632 if (*var_verify_map == 0) {
633 var_use_limit = 0;
634 var_idle_limit = 0;
635 }
636
637 /*
638 * Start the cache cleanup thread.
639 */
640 if (var_verify_scan_cache > 0) {
641 int cache_flags;
642
643 cache_flags = DICT_CACHE_FLAG_STATISTICS;
644 if (msg_verbose)
645 cache_flags |= DICT_CACHE_FLAG_VERBOSE;
646 dict_cache_control(verify_map,
647 CA_DICT_CACHE_CTL_FLAGS(cache_flags),
648 CA_DICT_CACHE_CTL_INTERVAL(var_verify_scan_cache),
649 CA_DICT_CACHE_CTL_VALIDATOR(verify_cache_validator),
650 CA_DICT_CACHE_CTL_CONTEXT((void *) vstring_alloc(100)),
651 CA_DICT_CACHE_CTL_END);
652 }
653}
654
655/* pre_jail_init - pre-jail initialization */
656
657static void pre_jail_init(char *unused_name, char **unused_argv)
658{
659 mode_t saved_mask;
660 VSTRING *redirect;
661
662 /*
663 * Never, ever, get killed by a master signal, as that would corrupt the
664 * database when we're in the middle of an update.
665 */
666 setsid();
667
668 /*
669 * Security: don't create root-owned files that contain untrusted data.
670 * And don't create Postfix-owned files in root-owned directories,
671 * either. We want a correct relationship between (file/directory)
672 * ownership and (file/directory) content.
673 *
674 * XXX Non-root open can violate the principle of least surprise: Postfix
675 * can't open an *SQL config file for database read-write access, even
676 * though it can open that same control file for database read-only
677 * access.
678 *
679 * The solution is to query a map type and obtain its properties before
680 * opening it. A clean solution is to add a dict_info() API that is
681 * similar to dict_open() except it returns properties (dict flags) only.
682 * A pragmatic solution is to overload the existing API and have
683 * dict_open() return a dummy map when given a null map name.
684 *
685 * However, the proxymap daemon has been opening *SQL maps as non-root for
686 * years now without anyone complaining, let's not solve a problem that
687 * doesn't exist.
688 */
689 SAVE_AND_SET_EUGID(var_owner_uid, var_owner_gid);
690 redirect = vstring_alloc(100);
691
692 /*
693 * Keep state in persistent (external) or volatile (internal) map.
694 *
695 * Start the cache cleanup thread after permanently dropping privileges.
696 */
697#define VERIFY_DICT_OPEN_FLAGS (DICT_FLAG_DUP_REPLACE | DICT_FLAG_SYNC_UPDATE \
698 | DICT_FLAG_OPEN_LOCK | DICT_FLAG_UTF8_REQUEST)
699
700 saved_mask = umask(022);
701 verify_map =
702 dict_cache_open(*var_verify_map ?
703 data_redirect_map(redirect, var_verify_map) :
704 "internal:verify",
705 O_CREAT | O_RDWR, VERIFY_DICT_OPEN_FLAGS);
706 (void) umask(saved_mask);
707
708 /*
709 * Clean up and restore privilege.
710 */
711 vstring_free(redirect);
712 RESTORE_SAVED_EUGID();
713}

719int main(int argc, char **argv)
720{
721 static const CONFIG_STR_TABLE str_table[] = {
722 VAR_VERIFY_MAP, DEF_VERIFY_MAP, &var_verify_map, 0, 0,
723 VAR_VERIFY_SENDER, DEF_VERIFY_SENDER, &var_verify_sender, 0, 0,
724 0,
725 };
726 static const CONFIG_TIME_TABLE time_table[] = {
727 VAR_VERIFY_POS_EXP, DEF_VERIFY_POS_EXP, &var_verify_pos_exp, 1, 0,
728 VAR_VERIFY_POS_TRY, DEF_VERIFY_POS_TRY, &var_verify_pos_try, 1, 0,
729 VAR_VERIFY_NEG_EXP, DEF_VERIFY_NEG_EXP, &var_verify_neg_exp, 1, 0,
730 VAR_VERIFY_NEG_TRY, DEF_VERIFY_NEG_TRY, &var_verify_neg_try, 1, 0,
731 VAR_VERIFY_SCAN_CACHE, DEF_VERIFY_SCAN_CACHE, &var_verify_scan_cache, 0, 0,
732 VAR_VERIFY_SENDER_TTL, DEF_VERIFY_SENDER_TTL, &var_verify_sender_ttl, 0, 0,
733 0,
734 };
735
